	        Send us your pictures   ·  Send us your stories Durban - Two Metrorail trains were set alight on Wednesday evening at the Durban and Berea stations in KwaZulu-Natal. Paramedics were called to Berea station on Wednesday at approximately 19:00 to find a train ablaze, said Garrith Jamieson, Rescue Care's operations director. "Rescue Care paramedics arrived on the scene to find a carriage well alight," he said. "The Durban fire department was in attendance and quickly extinguished the blaze before it spread." READ: Angry commuters torch trains, loot, at Cape Town station The second train was set alight at Durban station, he added. The fires severely affected traffic as Durban metro police closed off multiple routes around the stations while emergency personnel worked on the scene. Jamieson said passengers managed to evacuate the trains in time and no one suffered any injuries. "The cause of the fire is unknown at this stage. However, SAPS and the Durban Fire Department will be investigating further," he said. KEEP UPDATED on the latest news by subscribing to our FREE newsletter. - FOLLOW News24 on Twitter 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  